<font color="#FF0000">THANKS AND TEARS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jun 22 23:51:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Tom, Doc and others:<br><br>
I am a graduate student from red China. Maybe I do not have the right to attend your discuss, but I think you guys should know what your fighting in Vietnam meant to people living under the control of communists.<br><br>
You guys talked about destruction and human losses during the war. But do you really know the destruction and human losses after the communists won the war?--in Russia, in China, as well as in Vietnam.<br><br>
Communism is among the most evil forms of government this earth has ever experienced. They don't talk about people as human beings, but as SCREWs that will be fit into the giant machine called Socialism Construction, in whatever the way the Leaders like. They shrug off the death of millions of people---in China in the years of 1958-61, some four million from starvation!--- to be just unsuccessful social experiments.<br><br>
The tragedy of Vietnam war is: USA was not as strong as we thought it shoud be. USA could not give economic prosperity and human dignity to the people in poor countries; it even can't do anything about the human right violation in China and a lot of other countries. US is not strong enough to be the police for the world. The sacrifice you Americans made in WWII didn't secure a world in peace and harmony. And you couldn't win the Vietnam war!<br><br>
Even though I can assure you guys, based on what I have learnt from my 30 years of life in China, that you were fighting for a right cause in Vietnam, I can't erase the feelings of sadness and failure that you might have from the first war ever lost in US history.  But, you should know that you were fighting against a much powerful force at that time because it had promised everything to poor people that had not much future, and thus, gained their sacrifice in exchange; in Russia, China, East Europe as well as Vietnam. But it didn't fulfill its promises- promises it never intended to keep; the great social experiment sacrificed at least two generations-their souls as well as countless bodies; so, finally, it fell down in Russia, in east europe, and will some day in China and Vietnam; though it won't be  easy.<br>
While witnessing the fall of the Berlin Wall, you should regard it a part of the lost Vietnam War.<br><br>
War is a terrible invention but a reality in human history. At least you were fighting against an evil; have pity on those fought on the wrong side. It was a shame that you had to go out fighting when you were so young and knew little about what you were fighting against. It was a tragedy of the nation as well as the world. Hope you will feel better after hearing what I have to say. All those &quot;boat people&quot; would not have to flee their country, putting themselves in the mercy of the ocean, the pirates, and foreign governments, if ever you win that war! But, on the other hand, it should be a war of the Vietnamese; It is not Americans' duty to save the world from evil; but you did it any way--and failed. <br><br>
And, acturally, you had tried it before, in Korea. <br><br>
So, thank you Americans that had tried your best to save the world from the evil called Communism--believe it or not, it is true. Your sacrifice will be remembered by and your brave failure in Vietnam was sure a great tragedy to a lot of people once or now live under the rule of communism. <br><br>
I personally thank you all for forging America as it is now, a stronghold of democracy and personal freedom. After living in deep fear---when i was young, parents always warn children to obey by saying:&quot;A tiger will come and get you if you disobey&quot;. Nowadays, it is &quot;the police&quot; instead!; and the chinese government always puts an eye on its people even in a foreign country---for nearly 30 years, I am thankful to be here in the US, enjoying some of the freedom your forefathers and you have fought for and won for this promised land. Reading all these stories of your sacrifice and lost in Vietnam makes me cry. <br><br>
Tao @ Iowa State University
